                  </persName>
            . I am a Policeman. On the 4th of October, about a quarter-past four o'clock in the morning, I was on duty in the City-road, and proceeding down <placeName id="t18301028-200-crimeloc1123">Featherstone-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18301028-200-crimeloc1123" type="placeName" value="Featherstone-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18301028-200-crimeloc1123" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18301028-200-off1121 t18301028-200-crimeloc1123"></join> I saw the prisoner take a bag on his shoulder from the<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183010280089"></xptr>tail of a cart, which stood at a narrow court - a woman stood there: the prisoner went down the court with the bag - I and my partner went down the court, and met the prisoner returning without the bag; I asked what he had taken down the court - he said a few oats for his rabbits: the woman was his wife - Rowland went up stairs with them; I went up soon after, and found the bag in the middle of the room with this corn in it - the prisoner said he had brought it from his master, Mr. Holt, of Aldermanbury; that his master had given him leave, but he had taken too many - I took him in charge.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. PHILLIPS. Q. He gave you every facility to find his master? A. He did.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18301028-200-person1702">
                  WILLIAM 
                  ROWLAND
               <interp inst="t18301028-200-person1702" type="surname" value="ROWLAND"></interp>
